                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/628b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-01-20T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 20, 1936—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>23. In a conversation on the naval situation, the President expressed the opinion
                    that as far as any new agreement which may be negotiated <pb facs="0119" n="39"
                        xml:id="pg_39"/> at the Conference as now constituted is concerned, we
                    should still seek an agreement in the first instance within the tonnage limits
                    in the existing treaties, with an escape clause in the event Japan exceeds her
                    existing treaty limitations. You should, therefore, endeavor to make that your
                    first principle as the conversations proceed. The question of cruiser tonnage
                    increase, if insisted on, remains as previously outlined. In other words, you
                    should seek compensating decreases in other categories.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
